<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900530-0017</DOCNO><DOCID>900530-0017.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>05/30/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   STOCK PRICES SURGED as the earnings worries that joltedthe market Friday vanished. The Dow Jones Industrial Averagesoared 49.57 points to 2870.49, a record close. The Sandamp;P 500index also set a new high, its first since October. Bondprices rose steadily, while the dollar was mixed.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Revlon accepted new terms on a pending $1.8 billion bankloan amid regulatory pressure on banks to limit lending tohighly leveraged concerns.   ---   Xerox faces new write-offs at its Crum andamp; Forster insuranceunit that could approach $400 million, insurance-industryexecutives and analysts say.   ---   Ford told dealers it may nearly double incentives on 1990autos after next year's models go on sale in October. Thedisclosure may hurt the auto maker's sales this summer.   ---   Harcourt named former Energy Secretary John Herrington aschairman, succeeding William Jovanovich, whose son willfollow him as head of the publisher's executive committee.   ---   UAL's unions are talking to Chrysler Vice Chairman GeraldGreenwald about taking the top job at United Airlines if anemployee buy-out succeeds, sources said.   ---   Federal Express overcame an obstacle to efficiency as itwon clearance to merge its pilot seniority list with that ofTiger International, which Federal acquired last year.   ---   Westinghouse is expected to name Paul Lego chairman andchief executive in a move that could put the company on agrowth course.   ---   Equimark's Judith Fellheimer resigned her top managementposition, ending the bank holding company's husband-wifemanagement team.   ---   Massachusetts may adopt a 5% sales tax on professionalservices that are largely untaxed by states.   ---   Drexel's brokerage unit filed for Chapter 11bankruptcy-law protection along with 14 Drexel subsidiaries.   ---   William Farley's bondholders may seek to wrest from himvoting control of West Point-Pepperell. But the creditors maytry to avoid a forced liquidation of the firm because of aperception that Farley overpaid for it.   ---   The securities industry won a case in Supreme Court. Thejustices let stand a lower court's finding that Massachusettscan't stop brokerage firms from requiring customers to signarbitration agreements.   ---   Source Perrier agreed to sell most of its soft-drinkbusiness to Cadbury Schweppes for $211 million.   ---   Chase Manhattan is opening 10 offices nationwide to offerinvestment advice to well-off people who aren't wealthyenough to qualify for Chase's &quot;private banking&quot; department.   ---   Concern about Macy's creditworthiness led an insurer totighten its policy for firms with links to Macy.   ---   Tyco Laboratories agreed to buy the operating assets of anAustralian maker of fire-protection gear for about $600million in cash and stock.   ---   DHL International is selling minority stakes to Lufthansa,Japan Air and a Japanese trading company.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 137,410,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2870.49, up 49.57; transportation 1162.52, up 9.78; utilities213.97, up 2.70.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3360.61, up19.35.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.47, off 0.68;spot index 136.39, up 0.18.   Dollar: 151.25 yen, up 1.85; 1.6740 marks, off 0.0084.</TEXT></DOC>